programme.title: Life Story
programme.desc: David Attenborough reveals how the competition to breed creates scenes of the most extraordinary beauty, as well as some of the most violent battles seen in nature. A male flame bowerbird shows off its artistic prowess to impress a potential mate - but if that does not prove enough, it will demonstrate its dancing skills instead. Waved albatrosses pair up for life and spend hours in each other's company, although things are not so simple for a male peacock jumping spider - one wrong move in its dazzling courtship routine could prove fatal. However, one of the most magnificent displays of all is created by a tiny male pufferfish, which impresses the ladies by building a spectacular underwater 'crop circle' in the sand - arguably the most perfect and complex structure created by any animal(c)

He also examines the impact of a recent police shooting(c)

He is joined by prostitute Rita, who believes that she will escape from pending criminal charges if she takes part. After a series of mishaps, including the arrest and incarceration of the officer in charge of the project, the unlucky pair are abandoned and forgotten, only to wake up 500 years later in a world where the rampant breeding of stupid people has created a universally dumb society ruled by half-wits. programme.title: Almost Famous (2000)
programme.desc: Written and directed by Cameron Crowe, Almost Famous tells the story of a 15-year-old boy who, in the early '70s, is given the opportunity to go on tour with a rock band. William Miller's mother is overly obsessed with drugs and the negative influence of rock on teenagers. But he is a music lover and his hobby is to write about bands for an underground newspaper. The boy's work eventually catches the attention of Lester Bangs (Philip Seymor Hoffman), editor of a rock magazine who then asks him to cover a great concert. William manages to get only an interview with the opening band, Stillwater, but even so he wins the admiration of another editor, this time, of Rolling Stone. Now the boy has the opportunity to continue traveling with Stillwater and write an article that could open up the way to showbiz. During the tour he meets various interesting people, including a girl he falls in love with (Kate Hudson). Crowe, who received an Oscar for Best Screenplay for this film, wrote the story based on his teenage experiences, when he also contributed to Rolling Stone(n)
